I have been working with abstract super-classesc using elpy in conjuncture with jedi (v 0.9.0)  and have noticed that it is unable to locate definitions when working with a super class that expects part of its behaviour (a method) to be determined by a sub class.

I have attached a small piece of code to help reproduce the issue. In a nutshell, all jump to definition attempts are unable to locate the definition of the "func2" method that implements code expected by the super-class' "func1" method. In this example the call to the "func2" method within the "Super" class invokes a new inheritance tree search from bottom-up, which locates "func2" within the "Child" class.

    class Super():
        def func1(self, data):
            self.word = data
            print "Now within Super class - func1 method and self.word contains %s" % (self.word)
            self.func2()

    class Child(Super):
        def func2(self):
            print "Now within Child class - func2 method, self.word contains %s" % (self.word)

    i = Child()
    i.func1("test")

When the user attempts to jump to definition from the "self.func2" method call on line 5 no definition is located. I think the issue here is that jedi does not re-initiate an independent inheritance tree search to locate the definition, but rather expects it to be defined before the call.

